**Subchapter A – Permanent Investments in Families and Children**

**Sec. 70401. Enhancement of Employer-Provided Child Care Credit.** This section increases the amount of qualified child care expenditures employers can claim for the credit from 25% to 40% (50% for eligible small businesses). The maximum credit amount is raised to $500,000 ($600,000 for eligible small businesses), with both amounts subject to annual inflation adjustments starting in 2026.  An "eligible small business" is defined as one with average annual gross receipts of $5 million or less (previously $1 million). The credit is also expanded to include third-party intermediaries contracting with child care facilities.

**Sec. 70402. Enhancement of Adoption Credit.** This section makes a portion of the adoption credit refundable, up to $5,000 per year. The dollar amounts for the credit (currently $14,890) will be adjusted annually for inflation, using the 2001 calendar year as the base year.  The carryforward of unused credit is limited to five years. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70403. Recognizing Indian Tribal Governments for Purposes of Determining Whether a Child Has Special Needs for Purposes of the Adoption Credit.** This section clarifies that Indian tribal governments are recognized alongside state governments when determining if a child has special needs for adoption credit eligibility. This expands the definition of who can make that determination, potentially increasing access to the credit for adoptions involving Native American children. The change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404. Enhancement of the Dependent Care Assistance Program.** This section increases the maximum amount of expenses employers can cover under the dependent care assistance program from $5,000 to $7,500 ($3,750 for married filing separately). This allows employers to provide more assistance to employees with childcare expenses. The change takes effect for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405. Enhancement of Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit.** This section adjusts the income thresholds for the child and dependent care tax credit, increasing the applicable percentage used to calculate the credit. The applicable percentage starts at 50% and phases down for higher incomes, with a floor of 20% for taxpayers with adjusted gross incomes above $75,000 (or $150,000 for joint filers). The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Subchapter B – Permanent Investments in Students and Reforms to Tax-Exempt Institutions**

**Sec. 70411. Tax Credit for Contributions of Individuals to Scholarship Granting Organizations.** This section creates a new tax credit for individuals who contribute to scholarship granting organizations (SGOs) in states that voluntarily participate. The credit is up to $1,700 per taxpayer, reduced by any state credit received. SGOs must meet specific requirements, including serving students with incomes below 300% of the area median gross income. The credit applies to taxable years ending after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70412. Exclusion for Employer Payments of Student Loans.** This section permanently removes the sunset date on the exclusion for employer payments of student loans, up to $5,250 per employee. The $5,250 limit will be adjusted annually for inflation starting in 2026. The changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70413. Additional Expenses Treated as Qualified Higher Education Expenses for Purposes of 529 Accounts.** This section expands the definition of qualified higher education expenses for 529 plans to include elementary and secondary tuition, curriculum, tutoring (with certain licensing requirements), and online educational materials. It also increases the maximum amount that can be used from a 529 plan for K-12 expenses from $10,000 to $20,000. The changes apply to distributions made after the enactment date and taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025, respectively.

**Sec. 70414. Certain Postsecondary Credentialing Expenses Treated as Qualified Higher Education Expenses for Purposes of 529 Accounts.** This section allows 529 plans to be used for qualified postsecondary credentialing expenses, such as tuition for vocational programs and testing fees. A "recognized postsecondary credential program" must be included on a state list or meet other criteria. The changes apply to distributions made after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70415. Modification of Excise Tax on Investment Income of Certain Private Colleges and Universities.** This section modifies the excise tax on net investment income of certain private colleges and universities. The tax rates are tiered based on the institution's student adjusted endowment size (1.4% for $500k-$750k, 4% for $750k-$2M, and 8% for over $2M). It also clarifies that student loan interest and federally-subsidized royalty income are included as gross investment income. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70416. Expanding Application of Tax on Excess Compensation Within Tax-Exempt Organizations.** This section expands the definition of "covered employee" for the excise tax on excess compensation within tax-exempt organizations to include former employees who were employed after December 31, 2016. This broadens the scope of individuals subject to the tax. The change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Subchapter C – Permanent Investments in Community Development**

**Sec. 70421. Permanent Renewal and Enhancement of Opportunity Zones.** This section permanently renews and modifies the Opportunity Zones program. It changes the designation period to 10 years, establishes a decennial designation process, and revises the definition of "low-income community" to include a lower median family income threshold. The changes apply to areas designated after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70422. Permanent Enhancement of Low-Income Housing Tax Credit.** This section permanently increases the state housing credit ceiling and modifies the rules for tax-exempt bond financing. The credit ceiling increases to 1.12% of the state’s population. The requirements for tax-exempt bond financing are relaxed, allowing for a smaller percentage of financing to qualify. The changes apply to buildings placed in service after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70423. Permanent Extension of New Markets Tax Credit.** This section permanently extends the New Markets Tax Credit. It also adjusts the carryforward rules for unused credit, limiting the carryforward period to five years. The changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70424. Permanent and Expanded Reinstatement of Partial Deduction for Charitable Contributions of Individuals Who Do Not Elect to Itemize.** This section permanently increases the maximum charitable contribution deduction for non-itemizers from $300 to $1,000 ($2,000 for joint filers). The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70425. 0.5 Percent Floor on Deduction of Contributions Made by Individuals.** This section establishes a 0.5% floor on the deduction for individual charitable contributions. Contributions exceeding this threshold are allowed, but are subject to limitations. The section also includes rules for carrying forward disallowed contributions. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70426. 1-Percent Floor on Deduction of Charitable Contributions Made by Corporations.** This section establishes a 1% floor on the deduction for corporate charitable contributions, with a 10% ceiling. Contributions exceeding 1% of taxable income are allowed up to the 10% limit. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70427. Permanent Increase in Limitation on Cover Over of Tax on Distilled Spirits.** This section permanently increases the limitation on the cover over of tax on distilled spirits from $13.25 to $13.25. The changes apply to distilled spirits brought into the United States after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70428. Nonprofit Community Development Activities in Remote Native Villages.** This section provides a tax exemption for activities related to fisheries in the Bering Sea and Aleutian Islands carried on by certain Native Alaskan entities. This aims to support economic development in remote Native villages. The changes apply to the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70429. Adjustment of Charitable Deduction for Certain Expenses Incurred in Support of Native Alaskan Subsistence Whaling.** This section increases the maximum charitable deduction for expenses related to Native Alaskan subsistence whaling from $10,000 to $50,000. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70430. Exception to Percentage of Completion Method of Accounting for Certain Residential Construction Contracts.** This section modifies the rules for residential construction contracts, allowing for a 3-year election instead of the standard 2-year requirement. The changes apply to contracts entered into in taxable years beginning after the enactment date.

**Subchapter D – Permanent Investments in Small Business and Rural America**

**Sec. 70431. Expansion of Qualified Small Business Stock Gain Exclusion.** This section expands the qualified small business stock (QSBS) gain exclusion. It increases the exclusion percentage over time (50% for stock acquired on or before the applicable date and held for more than 5 years, tiered percentages for stock acquired after the applicable date) and increases the per-issuer limitation to $10 million (or $15 million, adjusted for inflation). The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70432. Repeal of Revision to De Minimis Rules for Third Party Network Transactions.** This section reinstates the previous $20,000 and 200-transaction threshold for third-party network transaction reporting requirements, reversing changes made by the American Rescue Plan Act of 2021. The changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70433. Increase in Threshold for Requiring Information Reporting With Respect to Certain Payees.** This section increases the reporting threshold for certain payments from $600 to $2,000. The $2,000 threshold will be adjusted annually for inflation starting in 2026. The changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70434. Treatment of Certain Qualified Sound Recording Productions.** This section allows qualified sound recording productions to be treated as qualified productions for the purposes of the section 181 deduction. It also sets a $150,000 limit on the amount of costs that can be expensed. The changes apply to productions commencing in taxable years ending after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70435. Exclusion of Interest on Loans Secured by Rural or Agricultural Real Property.** This section excludes 25% of the interest received on qualified real estate loans secured by rural or agricultural property. The changes apply to taxable years ending after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70436. Reduction of Transfer and Manufacturing Taxes for Certain Devices.** This section reduces the transfer and manufacturing taxes on firearms to $200 for machineguns and destructive devices, and $0 for other firearms. The changes apply to calendar quarters beginning more than 90 days after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70437. Treatment of Capital Gains From the Sale of Certain Farmland Property.** This section allows taxpayers to pay the tax on capital gains from the sale of qualified farmland property to qualified farmers in four equal installments. The changes apply to sales or exchanges in taxable years beginning after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70438. Extension of Rules for Treatment of Certain Disaster-Related Personal Casualty Losses.** This section extends the rules for treating disaster-related personal casualty losses. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the enactment date.

**Sec. 70439. Restoration of Taxable REIT Subsidiary Asset Test.** This section restores the 25% asset test for taxable REIT subsidiaries. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.



